<h3>Integral of a function</h3>
<p>Because we=E2=80=99re focusing on integral calculus, finding the integra=
l of a function is really at the core of our discussion. It=E2=80=99s the b=
asis for all those different types of integrals and methods we mentioned ea=
rlier.</p>
<p>Depending on the problem, you can find the integral of a function using =
several different methods:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://photomath.com/articles/substitution-method/">Substit=
ution</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://photomath.com/articles/partial-integration/">Partial=
 integration</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://photomath.com/articles/integrals-of-absolute-value-f=
unctions/">Integration of absolute value functions</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://photomath.com/articles/integrals-of-evenodd-function=
s/">Integration of even or odd functions</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Got a specific problem in front of you? Scan it with your <a href=3D"htt=
ps://photomath.com/install/">Photomath app</a> to learn how to find the int=
egral in that particular scenario.</p>
<h3>The meaning of integrals</h3>
<p>We=E2=80=99ve gone through all the definitions and background, but what =
does all of that really mean? Again, it depends on the context of the probl=
em, but an integral can tell you:</p>
<ul>
<li>The area under a curve on a graph</li>
<li>The area between a portion of a function and the <mjx-container class=
=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax=3D"CHTML" display=3D"true" tabindex=3D=
"0" ctxtmenu_counter=3D"6" style=3D"font-size: 123.6%; position: relative;"=
