<h3>Integral sign</h3>
<p>That squiggly, swirly, curly line is the hallmark of an integral, so whe=
n you see =E2=88=AB on the page, you know you=E2=80=99re dealing with an in=
tegral!</p>
<p>Fun fact: The shape of the integral sign is actually an elongated =E2=80=
=9CS=E2=80=9D standing for =E2=80=9Csum=E2=80=9D (it=E2=80=99s the Roman =
=E2=88=AB instead of the Greek =E2=88=91). The =E2=80=9CS=E2=80=9D for =E2=
=80=9Csum=E2=80=9D is based on the idea of adding the area of slices under =
a curve =E2=80=94 the more slices you divide the entire area under a curve =
into, the more precise sum you get. An integral is most precise because the=
 =E2=80=98=E2=80=99columns=E2=80=99=E2=80=99 of slices become infinitesimal=
ly thin. So cool!</p>
